04613nam a22007455i 9783110959994DE-B159720230228020105.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20111997gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831109599947 a10.1515/97831109599942doi  a(DE-B1597)45585  a(OCoLC)979755142  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aP299.A35 G45 1997bG45 1997eb 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a401.41a415  aET 6802rvk0(DE-625)rvk/28018:1 aGelderen, Elly van, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aVerbal Agreement and the Grammar behind its 'Breakdown' :bMinimalist feature checking /cElly van Gelderen. 1aTübingen : bMax Niemeyer Verlag, c[2011] 4c©1997  a1 online resource (222 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLinguistische Arbeiten ,x0344-6727 ;v36400tI-XIV -- tIntroduction -- t1 Lack of Agreement with Verb Subject I: Empty Expletives -- t2 Past Participle Agreement: Lack of Agreement with Verb Object -- t3 Lack of Agreement with Verb Subject II: Government -- t4 Lack of Agreement in Wh-Structures -- t5 The History of There -- t6 There-Expletives -- t7 Expletive It -- t8 Argument It: with and without Features -- t9 Indefinites: The Grammaticalization of Nouns -- t10 Coordinated Structures -- t11 Conclusion: Further Issues Regarding Agreement -- tReferences -- tIndex of Authors -- tIndex of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book is about what the 'lack' of agreement indicates about the structure of language. Rather than assuming that mistakes occur in languages, disagreement can be seen as an indication of a certain structural relationship. In a Minimalist framework, the partial agreement or complete lack of agreement is determined by when checking of case and agreement takes place and with what nominal element. Earlier work has shown that there may be variation regarding the number of functional categories a language activates. If that account is correct, languages with fewer functional categories (Dutch and Old English) will also have fewer specifiers and therefore less Spec-Head agreement. In these cases, government will play a role in the checking of case and agreement. There are, however, other reasons for the 'breakdown'. For instance, expletives play a major role and they may only be specified for some features (number or person) and when they agree with the verb, the 'real' subject does not. Two additional reasons are discussed: the impact from grammaticalization and from asymmetrical (e.g. coordinate) structures. The focus is on Modern, Old and Middle English and Dutch, but other Germanic languages (German, Swedish, Yiddish), Romance languages (Catalan, French, Italian, Spanish), Arabic, Chamorro, Hebrew, Hopi, Kirundi, O'odham, Navajo, and Urdu/Hindi are discussed as well.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aGenerative grammar. 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxAgreement. 0aMinimalist theory (Linguistics). 4aEnglisch. 4aSyntaktische Kongruenz. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Linguistics and Semiotics 1990 - 1999z9783110636895oZDB-23-DLS0 cprintz978348430364540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311095999440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110959994423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110959994/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DLSc1990d1999